# Fluff Date: 2026-02-16 11:04:06
overview:<p>The Stone Rhino was one of the most remarkable assault BattleMechs to emerge from the Clan Homeworlds, a one-hundred-ton monster whose origins trace back to one of the most infamous failures in military engineering history. In 2775, as Aleksandr Kerensky's forces tightened the noose around the Amaris Empire, Stefan Amaris's weapons programs grew increasingly desperate. The most notorious product of this frenzy was the SAM-RS2 Matar, a one-hundred-and-ten-ton superheavy BattleMech intended to single-handedly hold positions against an entire ’Mech company. Supervised by Senior General Rifkin Amaris (one of Stefan's closest cousins) the Matar project produced a machine of devastating theoretical firepower but catastrophic practical failure, as three separate design teams proved unable to resolve the stress issues that prevented the superheavy's leg actuators from moving the machine. The project was scrapped, its engineering staff executed for "treasonous incompetence," and the design passed into legend as "Amaris' Folly."</p><p>Decades later during the Golden Century, the Scientist Caste of Clan Smoke Jaguar seized upon recovered Matar blueprints as a challenge worthy of Clan engineering, an opportunity to prove their superiority by succeeding where the Inner Sphere had catastrophically failed. The resulting one-hundred-ton assault ’Mech was christened the Stone Rhino in honor of the nigh-indestructible beast native to Eden, and its devastating combination of firepower and durability quickly made it one of the most prized designs in any Clan touman. Produced in limited numbers, the Stone Rhino is known to the Inner Sphere by the reporting name Behemoth, one of the few Spheroid designations deemed acceptable by Clan warriors.</p>

capabilities:<p>The Stone Rhino carries an arsenal designed to destroy targets at range before they can close to exploit the design's limited mobility. A pair of Thunderstroke Series 2b Gauss Rifles mounted in the side torsos deliver punishing long-range firepower capable of crippling most ’Mechs in two volleys, while twin Kolibri Delta Series Large Pulse Lasers in the arms provide accurate medium-range fire. A single Chi Series Small Pulse Laser near the cockpit serves as a last-ditch defensive weapon. The design's most distinctive feature is its retractable, shock-absorbing weapon cowls covering each arm's weapon barrels, allowing MechWarriors to use the arms as battering rams in close combat without risking damage to the primary armament.</p><p>Powered by a Heavy Force 300 standard fusion engine, the Stone Rhino achieves a modest top speed of fifty-four kilometers per hour, supplemented by Grandthrust Mk 5 jump jets providing limited mobility over rough terrain. Eighteen tons of Compound 12A1 Standard armor afford reasonable protection for its weight class, though the ’Mech becomes dangerously vulnerable once it draws concentrated fire. This paradox defines the Stone Rhino's tactical legacy: its awesome firepower and historical prestige make it an invaluable asset, yet field commanders often cannot afford to risk losing one, resulting in machines that are sometimes held in reserve when they could be winning battles.</p>

deployment:<p>A Clan Hell's Horses variant produced at Tokasha Mechworks beginning around 3068, the Stone Rhino 3 strips away the Gauss Rifles and their ammunition dependency in favor of an energy- and missile-heavy loadout. Each arm mounts a pair of Large Pulse Lasers for accurate sustained fire, while twin ATM 9 launchers in the torso provide flexible engagement capability across multiple range brackets with four tons of ammunition. A pair of ER Micro Lasers cover the rear arc. The remaining tonnage is devoted to additional heat sinks, giving this variant the endurance for prolonged engagements that ammunition-dependent configurations lack.</p>

history:<p>The Stone Rhino's lineage begins with the Amaris Arms Corporation, a manufacturer created on Terra specifically to produce original BattleMech designs for the crumbling Amaris Empire. As Kerensky's liberation forces closed on Terra in 2775, Stefan Amaris demanded increasingly elaborate wonder weapons, and the Matar became the company's primary obsession. Designated SAM-RS2, the superheavy was designed for static defense, built around devastating long-range firepower: dual Gauss Rifles buried deep in the side torsos, supplemented by a dorsal-mounted Extended Range Large Laser. A pair of Large Pulse Lasers (one in each arm) provided the widest possible engagement arc against faster opponents, while a rear-mounted Medium Pulse Laser ensured there was no truly safe angle of attack. At Amaris's personal insistence, twin flamers were installed to deal with infantry. A Guardian ECM suite in one leg was intended to counter advanced munitions, though this placement precluded the installation of CASE to protect against ammunition detonation, a risk Amaris dismissed, confident that few enemies would survive long enough to threaten his creation.</p><p>For all its theoretical firepower, the Matar was doomed by fundamental engineering failures. At one hundred and ten tons, the design exceeded the structural limits of contemporary actuator technology, and three separate design teams proved unable to resolve the stress issues that prevented the ’Mech from walking. The superheavy never progressed beyond a single inoperable prototype. As Kerensky's campaign ground closer and news of inevitable defeat spread, morale within Amaris Arms Corporation collapsed. Amaris's cousins turned their rage on the engineering staff, executing them for "treasonous incompetence." Project lead Rifkin Amaris attempted to take the Matar data into exile but was apprehended by Kerensky's troops while trying to flee Terra. The recovered blueprints were carried into the Exodus, where they would lie dormant for decades.</p><p>During the Golden Century, Clan Smoke Jaguar scientists discovered the Matar plans in the vast archives carried from the Inner Sphere. Viewing the failed superheavy as a challenge to Clan superiority, they resolved to succeed where Amaris's engineers had failed. Working from the original specifications, the Jaguar scientists reduced the design to one hundred tons (eliminating the actuator stress problems that had doomed the Matar) while incorporating superior Clan-manufactured components that maintained comparable firepower in a lighter package. The resulting Stone Rhino entered limited production at Eden Consolidated Weaponry on Eden around 2847, christened after the nigh-indestructible beast native to that world. The design remained a prized Smoke Jaguar asset for centuries, with scattered examples appearing in other Clan toumans through Trials of Possession.</p><p>The Stone Rhino first stunned Inner Sphere forces during the Clan Invasion of 3049, where its sheer firepower caused mass panic among defenders unfamiliar with Clan technology. The design earned the Behemoth reporting name, a testament to the visceral impression it left on Spheroid MechWarriors. Despite bringing awesome firepower to the battlefield, the Stone Rhino's prestige and limited production numbers created a paradox: field commanders often could not afford to risk losing such a valuable machine, resulting in designs that were sometimes held in reserve when they could have been winning battles. Most Stone Rhinos in existence are ancient machines with long, storied histories and distinctive quirks born from centuries of service and repair.</p><p>Following the destruction of Clan Smoke Jaguar during Operation BULLDOG, the Stone Rhino's production history entered a turbulent new chapter. Clan Goliath Scorpion, scrambling to defend newly seized Jaguar holdings, revisited the original Matar specifications and rapidly developed a visually distinct but equally powerful second-generation Stone Rhino that entered production at Tokasha Mechworks. The Scorpions' hold on Tokasha proved short-lived, however, as Clan Hell's Horses captured the facility, inheriting both the production line and the expertise to manufacture new variants. When the Hell's Horses were ultimately ejected from the Clan Homeworlds, they established a new Stone Rhino production line at Csesztreg Industriplex Alpha on Csesztreg, ensuring the design's continued evolution well into the Dark Age and beyond. In a final irony, the ’Mech born from Amaris's most spectacular failure has endured for centuries as one of the Clans' most enduring assault platforms, a monument to the idea that even the worst designs can be redeemed by sufficiently determined engineers.</p>

